-- Japan, China, India, South Korea, Thailand: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- V. Ramakrishnan
-- 2010-07-15T22:06:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-15/japan-china-india-south-korea-thailand-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
cabinet meeting in the morning.  
 The Bank of Japan will publish at 2 p.m. in Tokyo its
monthly report on financial and economic conditions for July.  
 The Trade Ministry will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its
report on Japan’s demand for services in May. The tertiary
index, which captures 63 percent of the economy, fell 0.7
percent in May from April when it rose 2.1 percent, according to
a Bloomberg News survey of economists.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.08 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 87.45 per dollar at 6:46 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: China Muni Bond plans to sell 23.2 billion ($3.4
billion) of three-year debt today. China Development Bank will
sell 20 billion yuan of seven-year bonds today.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.55 percent. The yuan was at 6.7785 per dollar.  
 India: The government plans to raise 130 billion rupees
($2.8 billion) by selling bonds maturing in 2017, 2022 and 2027.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.64
percent. The rupee was at 46.61.  
 South Korea: The Ministry of Knowledge and Economy will
today publish data for June sales at major department stores.
Sales climbed 8 percent from a year earlier in May, a 15th
monthly increase.  
 The yield on the 4.50 percent bond due in March 2015 was
4.49 percent. The won was at 1,196.68.  
 Thailand: The central bank will publish foreign-exchange
reserves data for the week ended July 9 today. The holdings
totaled a record $147.8 billion as of July 2. The central bank
will sell 60 billion baht ($1.9 billion) of 14-day bills.  
 The yield on the 3.625 percent debt due in May 2015 was
3.03 percent. The baht was at 32.24.  
